{"key":"post-17736975","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17736975</id>\n<content>In the sense of accuracy, using wax paper or bubble wrap, etc., creates a mini-fruiting chamber just above the substrate.&amp;nbsp; It's not a casing.&amp;nbsp; A casing layer does part of this job, but a casing also holds moisture for the flush.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've done many trays in open air with no fruiting chamber just by using wax paper.&amp;nbsp; You can even fold it creatively and use on brf cakes.&amp;nbsp; I like the idea of the irregular surface of bubble wrap, and this is why we wrinkle up the wax paper first.&amp;nbsp; I would worry about the plastic though and its effect on the tops of the fruits as they push it out of the way.&amp;nbsp; Just be careful and lift it often to fan.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17737002</next>\n<prev>17736917</prev>\n<first>17736027</first>\n<last>28126722</last>\n<when>1359897516</when>\n<utime>02/03/13 03:18 PM</utime>\n</post>"}